> Thanks for taking the time to report this.
> Can you please attach an example that shows the issue or missing feature?  (Must be openly licensed, completely self-contained so can directly run what you provide. Ideally use test_regress format, see https://veripool.org/guide/latest/contributing.html?highlight=test_regress#reporting-bugs)
>
> What output from that test indicates it is wrong, and what is the correct or expected output?  (Or, please make test self-checking if possible.)

Here is a simple testcase that triggers the bug.

```sv
module bug(
    input bit in,
    input bit in2,
    output bit out
);
    bit internal = in;
    assign out = internal | in2;
endmodule
```

and the testbench 

```sv
module top;
    logic out;
    logic in;
    logic in2;

    bug dut (
        .out(out),
        .in(in),
        .in2(in2)
    );


    initial begin
        string line;
        int fd;
        int status;

        in = 'h0;
        in2 = 'h0;

        #20;
        in = 'h1;
        #20;

        $display("out: %b", out);

        assert(out == 0) else $fatal(0, "Assertion failed: 'out' is not 0 at the end of simulation");

        $finish;
    end
endmodule
```

Normally internal should initialise to 0 as it is a two state variable, whatever the value of in. Nevertheless in this example the initialisation seems to become a continuous assignement. As out takes the value 1.

This does not seem to be always the case as if I remove the in2 variable and the | then the result is what is expected. 

> What 'verilator' command line do we use to run your example?

```sh
verilator --binary --exe --build -Mdir obj_dir -sv --timing testbench.sv -I bug.sv && ./obj_dir/Vtestbench
```

> What 'verilator --version' are you using?  Did you try it with the git master version?  Did you try it with other simulators?

I am using git upstream `Verilator 5.043 devel rev v5.042-59-gf32095dd1`

> What OS and distribution are you using?

Linux arch

> May we assist you in trying to fix this in Verilator yourself?

Probably, if this does not seem to complicated I could investigate it.

> (Please avoid attaching screenshots that show text - you can convert images to text using e.g. https://ocr.space)

((Normally it is not a duplicate, sorry if it is))

